div.div:
We considered three model systems (

 Figure S2

) to investigate key factors, which affected the performance of PSC devices. First, to calculate optical properties (i.e., extinction spectra), model systems were constructed using Ag quantum dots with 10 nm diameter on top of ITO substrates with dimensions of 58 × 58 × 11 nm, and 20 nm (30 nm) thick ZnO (TiO

 2

) ETLs (

 Figure S2a

). Second, to calculate the spatial distribution of the electric field (to observe the near-field effect), a 90 nm thick PTB7:PC

 71

BM active layer was added to the previously described model system (

 Figure S2b

). To calculate the far-field scattering, we assigned Ag quantum dots as the main scattering object and changed the medium according to the corresponding ETL’s refractive index (i.e., ZnO and TiO

 2

) as shown in

 Figure S2c

. Periodic boundary conditions were applied to implement an infinite array into all systems. The ambient medium was air for the model systems used to obtain the optical properties and the near-field enhancements. For the far-field scattering calculation, the ambient medium was ZnO or TiO

 2

. The dipole spacing (

 d

) was set to 1 nm for all systems.

